<div id="review_428814493" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/428814493" />
    <a title="Philip" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7202471-philip"><img alt="Philip" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442604297p2/7202471.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/428814493?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Philip" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Philip" href="/user/show/7202471-philip">Philip</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780983348061" href="/book/show/13825969-thoughts-for-the-day">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer428814493" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2063922557169676347">This book offers a series of meditations on the Father, surely the most neglected Person of the Holy Trinity. The text explores a particular theme through a series of meditations, and then moves on to another theme. The writer draws from scripture and relates the meditations to various devotions that will be familiar to Roman Catholic readers. Some of the thoughts expressed here are quite inspirational.<br/><br/>The meditations were too brief for my taste. Many are a sentence or two long, and some consist</span>
  <span id="freeText2063922557169676347" style="display:none">This book offers a series of meditations on the Father, surely the most neglected Person of the Holy Trinity. The text explores a particular theme through a series of meditations, and then moves on to another theme. The writer draws from scripture and relates the meditations to various devotions that will be familiar to Roman Catholic readers. Some of the thoughts expressed here are quite inspirational.<br /><br />The meditations were too brief for my taste. Many are a sentence or two long, and some consist of only a sentence fragment. I also found myself distracted at times by the writer’s habit of capitalizing certain words to give them more emphasis. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2063922557169676347" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


